        <header class="page-header">
            <div class="container">
                <h1 class="page-title">Cities</h1>
                <p class="page-description">
                    Real markets, real players, real patterns. Theory meets
                    ground truth.
                </p>
            </div>
        </header>
        <section class="content-section">
            <div class="container">
                <div class="cities-layout">
                    <div class="cities-content-column">
                        <h2>Why Cities Matter</h2>
                        <p>
                            Real estate doesn't happen in the abstract. It
                            happens in specific places, with specific rules,
                            specific players, and specific constraints. Every
                            market has its own rhythm, its own politics, its own
                            unwritten rules about who builds what and where.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            I've spent years navigating European real estate
                            markets — not as a tourist, but as someone trying to
                            understand how value actually gets created and
                            captured. What I've learned is that the framework
                            matters less than the context. PropTech and ConTech
                            tools don't operate in a vacuum. They succeed or
                            fail based on local dynamics: regulation, ownership
                            structures, labor markets, capital flows, cultural
                            expectations.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            This section maps the cities I know best. Each one
                            represents a different lens on how real estate,
                            construction, and technology intersect. Not case
                            studies. Not sales pitches. Just ground truth.
                        </p>

                        <div class="city-selector">
                            <input
                                type="text"
                                id="city-search"
                                placeholder="Search cities..."
                                autocomplete="off"
                                onfocus="showCityDropdown()"
                                oninput="filterCities(this.value)"
                            />
                            <div
                                id="city-dropdown"
                                class="city-dropdown"
                                style="display: none"
                            >
                                <div
                                    class="city-group"
                                    data-search="italy lombardia milano"
                                >
                                    <div class="city-group-header">Italy</div>
                                    <div class="city-subgroup">
                                        <div class="city-subgroup-header">
                                            Lombardia
                                        </div>
                                        <div
                                            class="city-item"
                                            onclick="
                                                navigateToCity(
                                                    'milano/milano.html',
                                                )
                                            "
                                        >
                                            Milano
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                                <div
                                    class="city-group"
                                    data-search="germany berlin"
                                >
                                    <div class="city-group-header">Germany</div>
                                    <div class="city-subgroup">
                                        <div class="city-subgroup-header">
                                            Berlin State
                                        </div>
                                        <div
                                            class="city-item"
                                            onclick="
                                                navigateToCity(
                                                    'berlin/berlin.html',
                                                )
                                            "
                                        >
                                            Berlin
                                        </div>
                                    </div>
                                </div>
                            </div>
                        </div>

                        <h2>Milano</h2>
                        <p>
                            Milan is where Italian ambition meets European
                            capital. It's the country's financial center, its
                            design capital, and increasingly, its real estate
                            innovation lab. But it's also a city that moves at
                            its own pace — where relationships matter more than
                            term sheets, and where regulatory complexity can
                            kill a deal before it starts.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The real estate market here is fragmented.
                            Family-owned developers, institutional funds, and
                            global investors operate in parallel, often with
                            minimal overlap. PropTech adoption is selective:
                            sophisticated on the asset management side, patchy
                            on construction and operations. ConTech is still
                            niche, mostly confined to large-scale projects led
                            by international GCs.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            What makes Milan interesting is the tension between
                            tradition and transformation. The city is home to
                            some of Europe's most innovative architecture (Bosco
                            Verticale, CityLife) and some of its most ossified
                            bureaucracy. Navigating this requires patience,
                            local knowledge, and a willingness to play the long
                            game.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            I grew up here. I've seen the deals that work and
                            the ones that don't. Milan rewards insiders and
                            punishes shortcuts.
                        </p>

                        <h2>Berlin</h2>
                        <p>
                            Berlin is the opposite of Milan in almost every way.
                            Where Milan is polished and relationship-driven,
                            Berlin is raw and data-driven. Where Milan moves
                            slowly, Berlin moves fast — sometimes too fast.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The city has spent the last decade transforming from
                            Europe's affordable bohemian capital into one of its
                            hottest real estate markets. The result is a clash
                            of ideologies: startup culture meets rent control,
                            speculative development meets social housing
                            mandates, international capital meets local
                            activism.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            From a PropTech and ConTech perspective, Berlin is a
                            testing ground. The market is fragmented enough to
                            be accessible, liquid enough to be scalable, and
                            politically volatile enough to be unpredictable.
                            Regulations shift. Politicians intervene. Investors
                            get nervous. But the underlying fundamentals —
                            population growth, economic dynamism, housing
                            shortages — remain strong.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            I've spent time in Berlin's startup ecosystem, its
                            construction sector, and its policy debates. What
                            I've learned is that this is a market where ideology
                            and economics collide constantly. Understanding both
                            is the only way to build anything that lasts.
                        </p>

                        <h2>Other Cities (Coming Soon)</h2>
                        <p>
                            I'm expanding this section to include other European
                            markets where I have direct experience: London,
                            Paris, Barcelona, Munich. Each city represents a
                            different archetype of how real estate capital,
                            construction execution, and technology adoption
                            intersect.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The goal isn't to provide exhaustive market reports.
                            It's to map the patterns that repeat across borders
                            and the exceptions that define local markets. Real
                            estate is global in its capital flows but ruthlessly
                            local in its execution. This section is about
                            understanding both.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="cities-map-column">
                        <div id="map-container"></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
